Artifact Decompilation Report (Updated 2026‑04‑21)
Executive Summary

Ghatana’s vision of a bidirectional product compiler continues to hinge on two complementary pipelines: forward code generation from structured data and reverse extraction of a model from existing product codebases. The existing BuilderDocument and design‑system schema support forward generation, but a robust reverse pipeline is still emerging. Since the original report in April 2026, industry advances have reinforced the need for a loss‑aware ArtifactGraph and a normalized SemanticProductModel. New research on incremental parsing, knowledge graphs and design token standards highlights how a reverse compiler can remain performant and future‑proof. This update summarises those developments and proposes architectural enhancements and deliverables to align Ghatana with current standards.

Why This Matters

Model‑driven product development promises consistent design, governance and automation across UI, state, data and API layers. However, most organisations begin with an existing codebase rather than a greenfield configuration. Without decompilation, adoption is limited to new projects or full rewrites. A loss‑aware reverse compiler allows Ghatana to ingest real product repositories, extract a semantically rich model and regenerate code with provenance and confidence scores. Recent developments in design tokens, incremental parsing and cross‑language analysis broaden the scope of what can be extracted and ensure the reverse pipeline remains performant and standards‑compliant.

Repo Baseline

The Ghatana monorepo already contains many of the components required for bidirectional compilation:

UI builder: @ghatana/ui-builder provides a document model, import/export logic, code generation and abstractions like RoundTripFidelity and LossPoint.
Design system schema and registry: @ghatana/ds-schema defines component contracts, manifests and token schemas aligned with the Design Tokens Community Group. @ghatana/ds-registry stores components, token sets and themes.
Governance: @ghatana/ds-governance enforces contribution gates and ownership rules.
Real artifacts: the repository includes TypeScript/TSX components, Storybook stories, Prisma schemas, SQL migrations and Java services that serve as ground truth for reverse extraction.
Current Strengths
Round‑trip fidelity is valued: the UI builder’s support for confidence‑graded import and LossPoint tracking is the right foundation for lossy decompilation. Extractors can annotate confidence and residuals instead of hiding uncertainty.
Structured design system: component contracts already capture props, slots, events, metadata, examples and accessibility hints. Tokens follow DTCG structures and the registry stores reusable patterns.
Composable design: recipe‑driven composition and platform‑neutral render plans in @ghatana/design-system provide stable targets for reverse synthesis.
Current Gaps
Heuristic imports: TSX imports rely on regex scanning rather than AST or type‑aware parsing. HTML import is flat and heuristically parsed. This limits fidelity and misses cross‑file relationships.
BuilderDocument as the sole reverse target: real products include pages, layouts, database schemas, state stores, API clients and styles. A decompiler needs a richer canonical model than a component tree.
No repository‑wide symbol/provenance graph: there is no graph capturing exports, imports, route ownership, entity relationships, generated vs hand‑authored boundaries or style origins. Without this, it is difficult to answer questions about how a component is used or which schema defines an entity.
No explicit residual representation: unsupported expressions, custom hooks, imperative logic, SQL features and CSS constructs must be preserved as residual islands. Without a place to store them, loss becomes hidden.
Research Findings
Typed AST extraction as the primary reverse path for TS/TSX

The TypeScript Compiler API provides Program, CompilerHost and SourceFile abstractions that enable whole‑project semantic analysis. ts-morph offers a higher‑level API for authoring extraction passes. For TS/TSX, AST‑backed symbol resolution is essential to infer prop types, state, routes and hook usage.

Babel as a secondary parser

Babel’s parser and traverse stack provide fast syntax extraction and codemod‑style transforms for JS/JSX/TS. It can serve as a fallback when full type information is not available or when working with JS‑first repositories. However, it is insufficient for type‑rich product reconstruction on its own.

Tree‑sitter as a cross‑language substrate

Tree‑sitter offers incremental, incremental parsing across many languages. A 2026 article reports that Tree‑sitter re‑parses only changed regions, reducing parse times by up to 70 % on large files and improving error recovery. Tree‑sitter’s modular architecture supports dozens of grammars, making it an ideal structural index for TypeScript, Java, SQL and other languages in the repo. It also underpins knowledge graphs such as Codebase‑Memory, which builds a cross‑language graph over 66 languages and reduces token consumption by an order of magnitude while retaining ~83 % quality.

Lossless Semantic Trees and Moderne

OpenRewrite’s Lossless Semantic Tree (LST) representation preserves formatting, comments and type information beyond a standard AST, enabling safe, deterministic refactoring. Moderne extends LST to support Java, JavaScript and TypeScript with full type attribution and cross‑language control‑ and data‑flow analysis. LSTs could serve as the backbone for multi‑language extraction and faithful regeneration in Ghatana.

Storybook and Model Context Protocol

Storybook CSF defines component metadata and named stories; stories encode canonical prop sets, visual states and interactions. Storybook 10.3 introduces the Model Context Protocol (MCP) that allows AI agents to query real components, build UIs and run tests within Storybook. It also adds CSF Factory patterns across frameworks and improved accessibility with ARIA semantics and keyboard navigation. These features make Storybook an even richer source of semantic examples and testable states for decompilation.

OpenAPI 3.2.0 updates

OpenAPI 3.2.0 remains backward‑compatible but adds important features. Tag objects now support summaries and hierarchical relationships, allowing logical grouping of endpoints. The spec introduces first‑class streaming media types (e.g., text/event-stream, application/jsonl) with item schemas. It also extends the list of supported HTTP methods and introduces an additionalOperations field to define non‑standard verbs. Extractors should capture these details when constructing API models.

Prisma introspection

Prisma’s db pull command introspects a database and populates the Prisma schema with tables, columns, indexes and constraints. It can be run repeatedly to keep the Prisma schema in sync with the database. This pattern—extract what can be normalized and surface warnings for unsupported features—is a good template for Ghatana’s decompiler.

SQL canonicalization and diff

SQLGlot is a multi‑dialect SQL parser that can produce canonical abstract syntax trees, introspect ASTs and compute semantic diffs between queries. Using SQLGlot for SQL extraction allows normalization across dialects and enables tracking of schema evolution.

HTML living standard compliance

The WHATWG HTML specification is a living standard updated frequently; as of 19 April 2026, it remains current. parse5 adheres to this standard and should remain the default HTML parser for reliable extraction.

2026 Updates and Additional Research Findings

Since the initial report, several developments have further strengthened the case for a robust reverse compiler:

Stable design tokens specification (2025.10) – The Design Tokens Community Group published its first stable design tokens format. It provides a vendor‑neutral, production‑ready representation of colours, typography and component decisions, supports modern colour spaces like Display P3 and Oklch, and enables cross‑platform theming across iOS, Android, web and Flutter. Aligning token extraction and generation with this standard will future‑proof Ghatana’s design system.
Incremental parsing and knowledge graphs – Tree‑sitter 0.19.0 emphasises incremental parsing, re‑parsing only modified regions. Codebase‑Memory demonstrates that a Tree‑sitter‑based knowledge graph can drastically reduce token consumption while preserving quality. Building ArtifactGraph on similar principles will enable efficient, cross‑language extraction.
LST and cross‑language refactoring – Moderne’s extension of Lossless Semantic Trees to Java, JavaScript and TypeScript provides deterministic, type‑attributed refactoring across languages. Ghatana can adopt LST‑like IRs for faithful round‑trip regeneration.
Storybook 10.3 improvements – MCP allows agents to query live components, and CSF Factory patterns standardize example creation across frameworks. These features enrich story extraction and enable automated UI testing.
Extended API features – OpenAPI 3.2.0 adds hierarchical tags, streaming media types with item schemas and extended HTTP methods. Extractors must handle streaming responses and non‑standard verbs when constructing API models.
SQL canonicalization – SQLGlot’s canonical ASTs and semantic diffing can normalize multi‑dialect SQL and enable schema evolution tracking.

These updates underscore the importance of an extensible architecture that can ingest modern specifications, support incremental parsing and handle multiple languages without sacrificing fidelity.

Proposed Architecture

The overall architecture remains layered but incorporates enhancements based on recent research.

Layer 1: Artifact Inventory

Scan the repository and classify every file into families: components, pages/routes, stories/examples, tokens/themes/styles, API schemas, database schemas, domain/service code, configuration/build scripts and unknown. For each artifact record, capture its kind, language, framework guess, extractor eligibility, source path, import/export summary, checksum and incremental parse tokens. The inventory should integrate with a file watcher to trigger selective re‑extraction when files change.

Layer 2: ArtifactGraph

Create a repository‑wide graph of files, symbols, components, routes, styles, tokens, entities, database objects, stories and API endpoints. Each node includes source location, extractor version, confidence, provenance, privacy/security flags and residual fragments. Use Tree‑sitter 0.19.0 for incremental parsing, storing parse trees and cross‑language edges in a persistent knowledge graph. This graph enables low‑latency queries, call‑graph analysis and impact assessment across languages.

Layer 3: SemanticProductModel

Normalize the ArtifactGraph into product‑facing models: ComponentModel, PageModel, LayoutModel, TokenModel (aligned with the stable design tokens spec), ThemeModel, StyleModel, DataModel (from Prisma and SQLGlot extraction), ApiModel (supporting OpenAPI 3.2.0 features), BehaviorModel, PolicyModel, ObservabilityModel, StateModel, InteractionModel, CacheModel, WorkflowModel and ScriptModel. Each element carries provenance and confidence. Residual islands (CodeIsland, StyleIsland, QueryIsland, LogicIsland) store unmapped code with reasons and regeneration strategies.

Layer 4: Residual Model

Explicitly represent unsupported or partially supported constructs. Residual islands record the original source, normalized summary, reason for failure, review requirements and regeneration strategies. This prevents silent loss and allows progressive normalization.

Layer 5: Bidirectional Merge Engine

Add a merge engine that compares existing repo artifacts, the extracted SemanticProductModel and regenerated artifacts. Classify differences as safe normalization, semantic equivalence, manual review required or unsupported divergence. Use confidence and provenance to prioritise review. Round‑trip generation should preserve semantics rather than textual equivalence, with residual islands capturing non‑normalized regions.

Additional Architectural Enhancements (2026)

Recent research suggests several enhancements:

Incremental parsing and knowledge graph – adopt Tree‑sitter 0.19.0 for incremental parsing and build a persistent cross‑language knowledge graph akin to Codebase‑Memory. Each extraction updates the graph, enabling incremental re‑analysis and efficient querying.
Lossless Semantic Tree representation – use type‑attributed LSTs to preserve whitespace, comments and type information for Java, JavaScript and TypeScript extraction. LSTs support deterministic regeneration and safe transformations.
Design tokens spec alignment – integrate the stable design tokens format 2025.10 into token extraction and generation. Normalize CSS values into token candidates using modern colour spaces and cross‑platform categories.
Storybook CSF Factories and MCP – extend story extraction to recognize CSF Factories and metadata in Storybook 10.3. Use MCP to feed extracted component models to AI agents for testing and preview.
Extended API features – update the ApiModel to support hierarchical tags, streaming media types and non‑standard HTTP methods with additionalOperations. Map streaming sequences into typed event models.
SQL canonicalization and diff – incorporate SQLGlot to parse and canonicalize SQL, compute semantic diffs and support multi‑dialect normalization.
Persistent data model introspection – schedule regular Prisma introspection to keep the DataModel aligned with the database and record unsupported features.
Accessibility and inclusive design – capture ARIA roles, accessibility semantics and contrast requirements from components and stories. Extend the SemanticProductModel with accessibility conformance metrics and remediation guidance.
Reverse Extraction Strategy by Artifact Type
React components and hooks – Use the TS Compiler API for symbol and type extraction, ts‑morph for ergonomic traversal and JSX AST to recover element and slot structures. Analyze hook patterns for state and effects. Correlate with stories to infer props, variants and states. Represent residual logic in CodeIsland when imperative code cannot be normalized.
Pages and routes – Detect routes and layout hierarchies, extract route metadata, data dependencies, auth guards and SEO metadata. Use incremental parsing and call‑graph analysis to map component composition.
Styles and themes – Parse CSS and CSS‑in‑JS using PostCSS, extract custom properties and repeated values, and normalize them into design token candidates aligned with the 2025.10 spec. Detect theme overrides and residual CSS constructs.
Storybook stories and examples – Parse CSF files to extract component metadata, story args, decorators and parameters. Recognize CSF Factory patterns and link stories to components and variants. Use MCP to run tests and generate preview states.
Prisma schemas and SQL – Use Prisma introspection and parser to extract entity models, relations, indexes and constraints. Use SQLGlot to parse SQL migrations, canonicalize queries and compute diffs. Map both into a common DataModel and record unsupported features as residuals.
Java services and domain code – Use JavaParser or OpenRewrite‑based extractors to build LSTs for Java. Capture domain entities, service boundaries, API endpoints and persistence patterns. Use the knowledge graph to link Java services with TS front‑end models.
State management and caching – Analyze Redux, Zustand, Context or XState stores; extract state trees, actions, reducers and selectors. Recognize React Query, SWR or Apollo caching patterns; extract cache key structures, strategies and invalidation rules.
Message queues and events – Parse configuration files and code patterns for Kafka, RabbitMQ or AWS messaging; extract topics, schemas, subscriptions and consumer groups.
Build and CI/CD configurations – Parse YAML and build scripts to reconstruct workflows (GitHub Actions, GitLab CI, Jenkins) and job dependencies. Extract environment variables and secrets usage for WorkflowModel and ScriptModel.
Innovation Opportunities
Confidence‑scored extraction – annotate every extracted field with a confidence score, enabling the UI to prioritize human review. Provide per‑extractor diagnostics and lineage.
Provenance‑first modeling – capture where each model element came from, which extractor produced it and whether it was confirmed by a human.
Residual islands – preserve hard cases verbatim, storing code, style or queries that cannot be normalized and explaining why.
Multi‑source synthesis – synthesize model elements by combining artifacts (e.g., component implementation + stories + tests; page file + route config + auth wrapper; CSS + token definitions + story themes).
Semantic regeneration – focus on regenerating semantically equivalent code rather than byte‑for‑byte reproduction. Use formatting and linting tools to ensure stable output.
